            <h2>Lecture 4: Higher-Order Linear Differential Equations</h2>
            
            <h3>Higher Order Linear DE</h3>
            
            <p>The general form of an $$n^{th}$$ order linear DE is:</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$\frac{d^ny}{dx^n} + P_1(x)\frac{d^{n-1}y}{dx^{n-1}} + P_2(x)\frac{d^{n-2}y}{dx^{n-2}} + \dots + P_n(x)y = Q(x)$$
            </div>
            
            <h4>Linear DE with Constant Coefficients</h4>
            <p>If $$P_1(x), P_2(x), \dots, P_n(x)$$ are constants ($$k_1, k_2, \dots, k_n$$):</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$\frac{d^ny}{dx^n} + k_1\frac{d^{n-1}y}{dx^{n-1}} + k_2\frac{d^{n-2}y}{dx^{n-2}} + \dots + k_ny = Q(x)$$
            </div>
            
            <div class="example">
                <h5>Classification</h5>
                <ul>
                    <li>If $$Q(x) = 0$$, the equation is <span class="highlight">Homogeneous</span></li>
                    <li>If $$Q(x) \neq 0$$, the equation is <span class="highlight">Non-homogeneous</span></li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <h4>Solution Structure</h4>
            <p>The general solution is $$y = y_c + y_p$$ where:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>$$y_c$$ is the <span class="highlight">Complementary Function (C.F.)</span> - solution to the homogeneous equation</li>
                <li>$$y_p$$ is the <span class="highlight">Particular Integral (P.I.)</span> - particular solution to the non-homogeneous equation</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>The D-Operator Method</h3>
            
            <p>Let $$D = \frac{d}{dx}$$, $$D^2 = \frac{d^2}{dx^2}$$, etc. The DE can be written as:</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$(D^n + k_1D^{n-1} + \dots + k_n)y = Q(x)$$
            </div>
            <p>Or simply $$f(D)y = Q(x)$$.</p>
            
            <h4>Finding the Complementary Function ($$y_c$$)</h4>
            <p>To find $$y_c$$, we solve the homogeneous equation $$f(D)y=0$$.</p>
            <p>We form the <span class="highlight">Auxiliary Equation (A.E.)</span> by replacing D with m:</p>
            <div class="math-display">
                $$m^n + k_1m^{n-1} + \dots + k_n = 0$$
            </div>
            
            <h3>Cases for Roots of the Auxiliary Equation</h3>
            
            <div class="case-box">
                <div class="case-title">Case 1: Real and Distinct Roots</div>
                <p>If the roots $$m_1, m_2, \dots, m_n$$ are all real and different:</p>
                <div class="math-display">
                    $$y_c = C_1e^{m_1x} + C_2e^{m_2x} + \dots + C_ne^{m_nx}$$
                </div>
                
                <details>
                    <summary>Example: $$(D^2+5D+6)y=0$$</summary>
                    <div class="solution">
                        <p>A.E.: $$m^2 + 5m + 6 = 0$$</p>
                        <p>Factoring: $$(m+3)(m+2) = 0$$</p>
                        <p>Roots: $$m_1 = -3$$, $$m_2 = -2$$ (real and distinct)</p>
                        <div class="math-display">
                            $$y_c = C_1e^{-3x} + C_2e^{-2x}$$
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </details>
            </div>
            
            <div class="case-box">
                <div class="case-title">Case 2: Real and Repeated Roots</div>
                <p>If a root $$m$$ is repeated $$n$$ times:</p>
                <div class="math-display">
                    $$y_c = (C_1 + C_2x + C_3x^2 + \dots + C_nx^{n-1})e^{mx}$$
                </div>
                
                <details>
                    <summary>Example: $$\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + 4\frac{dy}{dx} + 4y = 0$$</summary>
                    <div class="solution">
                        <p>A.E.: $$m^2 + 4m + 4 = 0$$</p>
                        <p>Factoring: $$(m+2)^2 = 0$$</p>
                        <p>Roots: $$m = -2, -2$$ (repeated root)</p>
                        <div class="math-display">
                            $$y_c = (C_1 + C_2x)e^{-2x}$$
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </details>
            </div>
            
            <div class="case-box">
                <div class="case-title">Case 3: Complex Conjugate Roots</div>
                <p>If the roots are a complex conjugate pair $$m = \alpha \pm i\beta$$:</p>
                <div class="math-display">
                    $$y_c = e^{\alpha x}(C_1\cos(\beta x) + C_2\sin(\beta x))$$
                </div>
                
                <details>
                    <summary>Example: $$\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + y = 0$$</summary>
                    <div class="solution">
                        <p>A.E.: $$m^2 + 1 = 0$$</p>
                        <p>Roots: $$m = \pm i$$ (complex conjugate pair with $$\alpha=0, \beta=1$$)</p>
                        <div class="math-display">
                            $$y_c = C_1\cos(x) + C_2\sin(x)$$
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </details>
            </div>
            
            <h3>Practice Problems</h3>
            
            <details>
                <summary>1. Solve $$\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + 6\frac{dy}{dx} + 9y = 0$$</summary>
                <div class="solution">
                    <p>A.E.: $$m^2 + 6m + 9 = 0 \implies (m+3)^2 = 0$$</p>
                    <p>Roots: $$m = -3, -3$$ (Real and repeated)</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong> $$y = (C_1 + C_2x)e^{-3x}$$</p>
                </div>
            </details>
            
            <details>
                <summary>2. Solve $$(D^3 + D^2 + 4D + 4)y = 0$$</summary>
                <div class="solution">
                    <p>A.E.: $$m^3 + m^2 + 4m + 4 = 0$$</p>
                    <p>Factoring: $$(m^2+4)(m+1) = 0$$</p>
                    <p>Roots: $$m = -1$$ (real), $$m = \pm 2i$$ (complex, $$\alpha=0, \beta=2$$)</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong> $$y = C_1e^{-x} + C_2\cos(2x) + C_3\sin(2x)$$</p>
                </div>
            </details>
            
            <details>
                <summary>3. Solve $$(D^2+4)y = 0$$</summary>
                <div class="solution">
                    <p>A.E.: $$m^2+4 = 0$$</p>
                    <p>Roots: $$m = \pm 2i$$ (complex, $$\alpha=0, \beta=2$$)</p>
                    <p><strong>Solution:</strong> $$y = C_1\cos(2x) + C_2\sin(2x)$$</p>
                </div>
            </details>
        </div>
   